Working with Alignments
¶

In [1]:
# sudo apt-get update -y
# sudo apt-get install -y ugene

# sudo apt install prank

With UGENE installation also several tools are installed:

  • clustalw

  • clustalo

  • muscle

  • mafft

  • t-coffee

In [2]:
import Bio.SeqIO as IO

Info about input data and programms¶

Input data

  • Ogranism: Saccharomyces cerevisiae
  • Gene: SUP35
  • Protein: Eukaryotic peptide chain release factor GTP-binding subunit

Programs:

- ClustalW v2.1
- Clustal Omega v1.2.4
- MUSCLE v3.8.1551
- MAFFT v7.453
- Kalign v2.04
- t-coffee v11.0.8
- prank v.170427
- EMBOSS:6.6.0.0

Launch different alignment algorithms on the file SUP35_10seqs.fa¶

SUP35_10seqs.fa contains 10 sequences of the gene SUP35 from different S. cerevisiae strains

Note: it's better to save all files in fasta format for easier future comparison results from different programs with each other

ClustalW¶

Launch ClustalW with minimum parameters

In [3]:
! time clustalw -INFILE=SUP35_10seqs.fa

Compare algorithms on 10 sequences¶

algorithm alignment length (nt) time (seconds)
ClustalW 2148 3.30
MUSCLE 2275 3.02
MAFFT 2166 2.49
Kalign 2155 0.30
T-Coffee 2210 262.50
prank 2366 6.11

Conclusion: The best algorithm here is Prank. It has comparable speed with other algorithms and the highest length of alignment among them.

Strange file SUP35_10seqs_strange_aln.fa¶

As we can see there is one strange sequence in the file (highlighted) which does not match well with others.
It is connceted with that fact that this seqience is a reverse-complement. So, we should obtain it's reverse-complement and then realign sequences.

After reverse-complemet operation:

Compare algorithms on 250 sequences¶

algorithm alignment length (nt) time (seconds)
ClustalW 2179 1552.93
MUSCLE 2313 93.33
MAFFT 2322 15.11
Kalign 2214 15.07
t-coffee - -
prank 2472 102.53

Conclusion: here we can highlight two algorithms - MAFFT (it is the fastest one and has high alignment length) and Prank - it is a bit slower but has the highest length of alignment
